Name: ferrocene
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G
Rationale for classification: Not the transportation prohibition substance and not included in UNRTDG No. 3221 to 3241, though it contains  unsaturated bonds as chemical groups associated with self-reactive properties present and Fe-C bonds as chemical groups with explosive properties present.

Name: Benzene, diethenyl-
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G
Rationale for classification: Although the grouping relevant to autoreactive was included in the molecule but includes a polymerization inhibitors are does not polymerize in room temperatures. So it was taken as Type G.

Name: Carbon black
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Not classified(Materials of animal or vegetable origin), Classification not possible(Materials of mineral origin)
Rationale for classification:
It is based on the Animals-and-plants system materials: UN number 1361 (CARBON, animal or vegetable origin, Class4.2, Packing Group IIorIII).
Mineral systems materials: no data.

Name: (E)-3-(dimethylamino)-1-methyl-3-oxoprop-1-enyl dimethyl phosphate
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G

Name: Styrene, methyl-
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Not classified (with stabilizer)

Name: chlorophenol
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Not applicable (o, m, p-)
Rationale for classification: Containing no chemical groups with explosive or self-reactive properties present (o-, m-, p-)

Name: Dichloroethylene
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Classification not possible (1, 1-form), Not classified (1, 2-form)
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data, though containing unsaturated bonds. 1, 2-form is classified into Class 3 (UN#1150) (UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods).

Name: Sodium azide  (Na(N3))
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G
Rationale for classification: Not classified in UNRTDG Class: 4.1, but Class: 6.1 (though containing azido groups)

Name: 1,1'-Dimethyl-4,4'-bipyridinium salts (except paraquat dichloride)
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Not applicable (diiodide), Not classified (dimethylsulfate)
Rationale for classification:
Containing no chemical groups with explosive or self-reactive properties: commercial 1,1'-dimethyl-4,4'-bipyridinium=diiodide.
Not classified due to lack of data, though containing chemical groups (sulfonyl) with self-reactive properties: 1,1'-dimethyl-4,4'-bipyridinium=dimethylsulfate. Classified into Division 6.1 (UN#2781, bipyridinium pesticide, solid, toxic) (UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods)

Name: methylhydrazine
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G

Name: Arsenic acid
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Not applicable (aqueous solution)
Rationale for classification: Containing no chemical groups with explosive or self-reactive properties

Name: Mevinphos
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G

Name: 2,2'-Azobisisobutyronitrile
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type C
Rationale for classification: Not classified as explosives and "Not applicable" as oxidative solids and organic peroxides; the decomposition heat is 1.3kJ/g (Bretherick (J) (5th, 1998)), while SADT stands at 50degC (Studies in Disasters (2002)) - which correspond to "self-reactive substances." With no data available for classification, the substance is classified into "Type C," according to the classification by UN Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods: Self-reactive Substance C (Solid) (Thermal Control Required), Class (Category 4.1 Container: No Grade (UN#3234).

Name: butenone
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G

Name: Pentachloronitrobenzene
Classification: Self-reactive substances and mixtures - Type G
